caption: We've eaten here once since COVID-19. The outdoor picnic-style seating was nice, and the customer service was good as usual. I also appreciated how clearly diet restrictions were labeled on the menu (vegan, gluten-free, etc). Our gyoza was delicious! My only complaint is the ramen. It was WAY too oily. And not even that flavorful. I ordered extra noodles, which made the flavor issue worse. It came on the side in a cup, and the noodles had partially congealed together. Before the pandemic their ramen was always top notch, and I would have given them 5 stars. I hope they get back to where they were before.

Absolutely delicious food and fast service. They are very Covid-19 careful and have seating set up only outdoors. In fact, you don't even enter the establishment to order, they have an order center set up outside as well. All bowls and cutlery are disposable, but quality and recyclable disposable. We had three varieties of ramen and all were outstanding, although I prefer the smooth, rich flavor of Tonkatsu, which was my favorite. The regular order size is quite large and could be shared. The smaller portion is perfect for one. The house made kimchi was crunchy, saucy and umami-rich, I recommend that as well. We will be going back for sure.
Menu has lots of options. This was my first time having ramen and I loved it. The taste is not too strong and extremely savory.
Different and very good. A must try.
Excellent food that was both tasty and arranged well. I love the broth. Cocktails balanced flavor with strength. All outdoor dining during covid.

Love the way they’re handling carry out right now. It was easy to order online, pickup was no hassle, and they separate the ingredients from the broth so that everything stays fresh during transport. The broth is easy to reheat at home too so everything tasted like it would at the restaurant. Very happy with my experience!
Delicious and fresh ingredients. Bring a 😷because it's required to order food even sitting outside

All types of asian cuisine are our favorite foods. We make asian at home regularly. we bought the ramen at the end of the business day and not only did they not give us enough broth. it had no flavor. I'm thinking it was watered down just so they could make a sale before they closed. Cost me over $30 for 2 soups. Don't go there!

I got the tonkotsu ramen and my husband the shiyo. My chasu and egg were delicious, but my broth was a little oily for my taste. The shiyo was clean and yummy, but the chasu was tough and egg was just a regular hard boiled egg. Overall very good.

Beautiful Day, outside seating, lovely ramen--what more could one want! Crane Ramen is rising above a bad time for the restaurant industry with excellent, safe service and delicious food! You won't regret this choice!

I normally go to Taste Noodle House on 34th, I work right there and it's close to my house, but tonight was my freedom celebration and wanted to try something different. I have heard and read how truly amazing Crane Ramen was I needed to try it for myself. I was looking for a chicken or seafood ramen, I don't eat pork or beef and wanted it with a heavy miso broth. Since today was my freedom party, I didn't care if it had pork or beef broth I just didn't want the meat to be of that persuasion. I drove there and spoke one-on-one with the host/server and she was extremely helpful and helped me make a selection based upon what she thought I wanted (she had about 12 tables, was juggling to go orders on the phone and walk-up Togo orders) She was doing an amazing job as I am a bartender myself. I have to say I was a little disappointed in the soup. The broth was dark but light in flavor and did not have much substance. No miso, the chicken was bland and overcooked, especially being dark meat (kind of hard to do), and the corn displayed in the photo looked as if it was on the cob or at least shucked off the cob, and this looked like it was canned. The egg was delicious, bok choy okay, but just felt like it was missing so much! Flavor, me too, mushrooms, don't know. I've just heard so much hype about this place and as I sit here in my living room eating my soup, unfortunately I'm disappointed. I never like to give reviews like this ever ever. As I read the other reviews, everybody seems to think this is the best restaurant in the world so I'm thinking perhaps I might have had a bad experience. I certainly hope so. Perhaps I just ordered the wrong dish for what my liking was. I did ask for guidance and explained in detail what I was looking for and craving. So somewhere along the line something was lost and translation or perhaps this is just not the soup for me. I will definitely give them another chance since they are the talk of the town, but at $15 a pop, it's kind of hard to take a risk,again, if you were told this was the soup with the most flavor.. and it just not seem to be cutting it for even subtle flavor. I even added the normal things that I add to pho/ramen, and it did not cut the mustard. Perhaps I need to add mustard LOL JK. Maybe I just ordered the wrong thing....I hope so.

Wife and I stopped by here for dinner on 12/9 (Wednesday). We ordered the Roasted Pork Belly Buns, the Tonkotsu, and the "Spicy Ramen" (Spicy Paitan).  The Bao bun and the veggies (in the bun and the ramen) were all great, very fresh. The broth in both ramens was awesome, comparable to some of the best ramen places in Chicago, Atlanta, etc (was pleasantly surprised). Unfortunately, the meat in all 3 dishes held it back a bit. The pork belly, pork chasu, and pulled pork had flavors that were just okay (?under marinated) and definitely could have use a bit more char/browning. Maybe it's just the way they do pork? Either way, I'm pretty sure the ramen would be great if you got a vegan/vegetarian option.  I'm a little dumbfounded about how you can make such wonderful broth (which is the hard part, in my mind), go through the trouble to have great fresh vegetables, but miss the mark so much in regards to the meat! I will add that the Ramen egg probably would have benefitted from being marinated a bit longer, but was okay as is. I really want to like this place and look forward to trying it again - something non-pork probably.

10102020: Done correctly, Tonkotsu Ramen is satisfying bowl of warm umami. You will not go wrong with this dish. From the savory, almost creamy pork bone broth, the cut of pork with fat marbling, or the pickled eggs this dish satisfies. Though enjoyable anytime of the year, this dish should be mandatory consumption during dank, winter days. A big, soft blanket meal for your tummy. The Tofu Buns were like biting into a soft, pillowy cloud and were equally enjoyable. There was an order of Kimchi Brussel Sprouts too with kimchi puree on the side. With or without the sauce, the aggressively roasted brussel sprouts were an enjoyable side. So why 4 stars? First time eating here and there are other items in the menu yet to be tried. Off to a good start though, that's for sure. Go. You'll be happy.

The service was great. Really nice server. The food however was disgusting. Vegi miso and gyoza was my order. The soup was cold and beyond greasy, the noodles tasted old and the vegetables were sparce. The gyoza tasted like soap or very strong cilantro not sure but not good. For the price this is unacceptable. 4 other people I was with had the same expirence, maybe it was a bad day im not sure. What I am sure is I would not reccomend this or go back again.

Terrific ramenya in the heart of downtown. The prices (the ramen were $12 - $14) were appropriate for the quality & portion sizes (except for the kara-age chicken appetizer, which was a bit stingy). The servers were efficient and very engaged. They were friendly, but not intrusive...just right. The ramen broths were all excellent (my tonkotsu was very rich and delicious), and the noodles had that springy bite that is indicative of quality Japanese noodles. Also, the ajitsuke tamago were at that perfect sweet spot between soft- & hard-boiled, where the yolks are pleasantly creamy. We especially enjoyed the gyoza, which were properly well-crisped on just the one side, and had a delicious filling. One member of our party disliked ramen, and there were several other options on the menu that pleased her, including the Hiyashi Chuka, a cold noodle dish with s ginger dressing. There are lots of vegetarian options, as well, We were there for an early dinner, but I could see that their small dining room filled up fast, and they don't do reservations, so expect a brief wait. Personally, I'm looking forward to my next visit.

Unbelievably good food. I’d only heard about the authentic ramen trend in recent times, but hadn’t gone looking for it as I was content with my view of ramen being staple college dorm food. Wandering around Gainesville for the weekend, my wife and I literally walked a few blocks looking for something to eat for lunch on a Sunday and found this place.  The first thing we wanted to try was the Gyoza, and it was so perfect it literally melted in our mouths with deliciousness. I don’t think I can ever order pork dumplings at a Chinese takeout place again knowing these exist, they were that good.  As for the ramen, well... just like I told our server (who patiently explained the detailed process of how they cook their 3 main broths)... you had me at snow crab and pork belly. The fresh vegetables, soft boiled egg, texture-perfect noodles and that warm, rich broth all come together for a truly satisfying dining experience.  And then... I tried my wife’s chicken bowl which had ginger in the broth, which I liked even better than my own. As I told my wife about half way through, I could eat this nourishing, delicious food every day. If there’s one place I know for sure we will visit again when in Gainesville, it is definitely Crane Ramen.

It was my first time experiencing Gainesville's top shelf ramen scene. People who went always lauded it's food as rich and flavorful. Excited, I decided to give it a try. Upon arriving, I was promptly seated. Their decor and customer service are top notch and passable respectively. I ordered the ramen with chicken in it. (More on why I dont remember the name shortly). The food arrived promptly and the plating was excellent. Starting with the broth (which was a pitiable amount), the food was overwhelming salty and the soy sauce shone as the star flavor. The Vegetables and chicken on top of the ramen had grown cold due to the lack of thermal insulation around it. The egg was like the broth. Salty and lacked any resemblance to it's former incarnation of being an egg. Instead it had been reborn as a soy flavored monstrosity. The noodles were the only reedeming feature of the dish. It retained the flavor of the broth while not being overly strong. Overall, the ramen can only be described as a disappointment. The broth to noodle ratio was so pitiable I had to add water to balance it out and reduce the saltiness. The dish was so unmemorable I don't even remember exactly what it was I ordered. However I will admit that it seemingly tastes very much of what one can expect in America. The umami and saltiness were overwhelming and completely unbalanced as one would expect of the more mild flavored Japanese cuisine. In conclusion, I would come back if not for the high price tag for a dish that seemingly is not deserving of it.

The whole menu is delicious and the service is awesome. I recommend sitting at the bar to watch the chefs in action. My fav is the Spicy Pork Paitan. It is multilayered-savory. Marvelous. Paired with the Bit the Bullet cocktail adds a light sweet and pleasant aromatics to the palette.

Between eating delicious food and falling in love with our server, this place was heavenly.  The night started poorly. Internet on the block was down and the wait list was long, but I wanted ramen.  After waiting about an hour and a half, we were seated a small table and we're greeted by our server--I wish I remembered her name (I blame my lapse in memory on drinking a very strong gin drink at a local bar while waiting for our table) but she had blonde hair and wore round glasses with a black/grey tortoise pattern. She was welcoming, patient, warm, hilarious, and intuitive when it came to knowing what to suggest from the menu for us. While ordering appetizers and asking about the ramen, our server made both a recommendation for the spicy ramen and a Pokemon reference. I was sold. She continually checked in on us and was supportive even when we ordered a second round of steamed buns AFTER we had received our ramen. It's rare to find people in hospitality that truly care about other people's experiences but our server was one of them.  The house made kimchi was delightfully pungent with a decent amount of kick. My boyfriend always eats kimchi by itself. I've never had the urge to do so until last night at crane ramen. The steamed buns, one of my favorite treats in the world, were fresh and flavorful. The pork belly was tender, fatty, and it melts in your mouth. I tried to take as many bites as possible to savor it but we still ordered more buns later in the meal because we didn't get enough. My spicy pork ramen was especially satisfying since it was a chilly evening. The broth was perfectly rich and spicy. Our server suggested A yuzu honey ice cream for dessert. Normally, I would not order ice cream at a restaurant but I had yet to be disappointed. The ice cream was an ideal pairing of tartness from yuzu and a smooth, subtle sweetness from the honey. The ice cream had this surprisingly pleasant texture of layers creamy smooth cream juxtaposed with thin sheets of ice.  tl;dr Fantastic service and delicious food!

This restaurant is far too pricey for what it offers. We had a short (~20 min) wait to get in which is acceptable for the city but we also had to wait a while for our food to come out which is unacceptable for a ramen bar. I was torn between the inviting modern facad that encouraged parties to overstay their visit and the expectation of fast service that ramen is known for that was just not met. While the restaurant itself was decorated quite nicely, it was quite warm inside which made me want to leave asap, especially after eating hot food (with room temperature water). The ramen was okay, I felt that the broth and noodles were fine but the vegetables were cooked very unevenly. Regardless, I thought $12 for a vegetarian bowl is ludicrous to expect, especially with tip. My favorite item was the agadashi tofu steamed bun which was actually quite nice. It was probably a mistake to try this restaurant on a Friday night . We arrived at about 8pm  and our 1/2 hour wait turned into an hour.  And, as usual when you're waiting for a table, it seemed others arriving later than us were seated before us...  When we finally got a table, in the front, it was as hot inside as it was out.  Before we sat, the waiter poured out glasses of room-temperature water for our table.  The bottle was classy but we had to ask for ice.  And that was the last time we discussed drinks with our waiter.  He rushed in, took our food order and rushed off.  I don't know that we would have head him though, it was extremely loud in the small space.  Even in such a small restaurant it took a while before we saw him again and by that time we were really just waiting it out in the heat, hoping that the food would live up to its reputation.     Unfortunately, when it arrived 1/ 2 hour later, while it was good it didn't make the wait and poor service worth the while.   We have heard quite a bit of high praise for Crane Ramen  from our friends but the impression I left with is that they are coasting on their initial reputation and aren't putting out the effort they once did.  I am willing to believe that our visit was atypical.  Perhaps the hostess and waiter were having a bad day.  Maybe they were having issues with their air-conditioning and the night's clientele were especially loud talkers.     And the refrigerator they cool their drinking water in was dead.    I would recommend it for the food alone if you catch it at a better time.
